{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee261ce0-8dd4-422e-9701-ae862b9cd1e8","content":"Your tutorial is **partially correct**:\n\n### ✅ `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — Correct\nThis is the standard .NET MAUI iOS platform-specific. Add the namespace and apply it:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nThis keeps content within the safe area (away from the notch/Dynamic Island and home indicator).\n\n### ❌ `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` — Not a real property\nThere is no built-in `IgnoreSafeArea` property on `Grid` or any layout in .NET MAUI. That tutorial is incorrect or referencing a third-party library.\n\n### Background image workaround\nTo have a background image extend *behind* the safe area while keeping other content safe, use `BackgroundImageSource` on the page (it naturally fills the full screen), or layer your layout:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n  <Grid>\n    <!-- Full-bleed background -->\n    <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n    <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n    <Grid Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='20,60,20,34'}\">\n      <!-- your content here -->\n    </Grid>\n  </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nFor a dynamic approach, you can read `SafeAreaInsets` from the platform and bind padding at runtime rather than hardcoding values.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a79d44f6-54a4-4d65-8ab6-4643cac17bcd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"No matches in this repository. Let me answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI.\n\nFor .NET MAUI (including .NET 10):\n\n1. **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** - This is a valid iOS platform-specific in .NET MAUI. You need the namespace `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"`. This tells the page to respect the safe area insets on iOS, pushing content away from the notch, home indicator, etc.\n\n\n2. **`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** - This isn't a standard .NET MAUI property, so it won't work on Grid or other layouts. To get a background image extending behind the safe area while keeping other content within bounds, I'd set `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on the page and use the page's `BackgroundImageSource` property or position the image appropriately.\n\nLet me reconsider though—I want to make sure I'm not missing something from newer .NET versions. `Page.UseSafeArea` is definitely the iOS platform-specific approach, and for individual views that need to ignore safe areas, I'd typically adjust padding and margins or use custom handlers. I'm fairly confident `IgnoreSafeArea` doesn't exist as a built-in property in .NET MAUI, so that tutorial is likely outdated or incorrect. The standard approach is using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` on the page level and then managing individual view positioning through margins and padding.","outputTokens":947,"requestId":"A42C:1D28CE:53851C:6138B1:69F008A1"},"id":"f4fc5ced-c38e-4ca0-9098-a0ca8b9790c9","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:09:10.749Z","parentId":"fb23d8dc-008e-44fa-a545-0577fce81465"}
